Case Study: A human breast atlas integrating single-cell proteomics and transcriptomics

Kayla Interdonanto

Roswell Park Comprehensive Cancer Center
Kayla.Morrell@RoswellPark.org

31 October 2022

Source: vignettes/hca-9b876d31-0739-4e96-9846-f76e6a427279.Rmd

Setup

Load useful packages

library(hcaCaseStudies)
library(hca)
library(dplyr)

Project information

Set the project id

project_id <- "9b876d31-0739-4e96-9846-f76e6a427279"

Display information about the project

project_information(project_id)
## Title
##   A human breast atlas integrating single-cell proteomics and
##   transcriptomics
## Contributors (unknown order; any role)
##   Jia-Ren Lin, Peter K Sorger, Aviv Regev, Rachel Schwartz, Laura M
##   Selfors, Kurt D'Andrea, Sandro Santagata, Walter L Goh, Deborah A
##   Dillon, Jennifer M Rosenbluth, Ron C J Schackmann, Carman Man-Chung
##   Li, Shaolin Mei, Katherine L Nathanson, Kaitlin Moore, G Kenneth
##   Gray, Nomeda Girnius, Judy E Garber, Joan S Brugge, Hana K Shapiro
## Description
##   The breast is a dynamic organ whose response to physiological and
##   pathophysiological conditions alters its disease susceptibility, yet
##   the specific effects of these clinical variables on cell state remain
##   poorly annotated. We present a unified, high-resolution breast atlas
##   by integrating single-cell RNA-seq, mass cytometry, and cyclic
##   immunofluorescence, encompassing a myriad of states. We define cell
##   subtypes within the alveolar, hormone-sensing, and basal epithelial
##   lineages, delineating associations of several subtypes with cancer
##   risk factors, including age, parity, and BRCA2 germline mutation. Of
##   particular interest is a subset of alveolar cells termed
##   basal-luminal (BL) cells, which exhibit poor transcriptional lineage
##   fidelity, accumulate with age, and carry a gene signature associated
##   with basal-like breast cancer. We further utilize a medium-depletion
##   approach to identify molecular factors regulating cell-subtype
##   proportion in organoids. Together, these data are a rich resource to
##   elucidate diverse mammary cell states. Overall design: A total of 16
##   breast samples were assayed (4 samples from reductive mammoplasties
##   and 12 from prophylactic mastectomies).
## DOI
##   10.1016/j.devcel.2022.05.003
## URL
##   https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/35617956/
## Project
##   https://data.humancellatlas.org/explore/projects/9b876d31-0739-4e96-9846-f76e6a427279

Conventions

Statistics calculated locally use local.* for column names, e.g., local.cellCount.

project_filter <- filters(projectId = list(is = project_id))

## create `files2` with just the files needed for count-matrix
## analysis

files2 <- files1 |>
    filter(fileFormat == "csv.gz")

Retrieve and cache locally all files needed to construct a gene x cell count matrix.

file_path <-
    files2 |>
    files_download() |>
    setNames(files2 |> pull(name))

## join file path to appropriate components of `f`
count_matrix_files1 <-
    files2 |>
    left_join(tibble(
        fileId = files2$fileId,
        local.filePath = unname(file_path)
    ), by = "fileId")

We can extract some data from the files, e.g., cell and gene counts

## 'files' is the final, locally modified, version of file data
count_matrix_files <-
    count_matrix_files1 |>
    filter(name == "GSE180878_Li_Brugge_10XscRNAseq_GeneCellMatrix_RNAcounts_human.csv.gz") |>
    cell_count_csv() |>
    gene_count()

count_matrix_files |>
    select(name, local.geneCount, local.cellCount)

Count matrix

Create a dgCMatrix sparse matrix (defined in the Matrix package). Save it in the package cache for re-use across R sessions.
